## Phase 2

### Goal

Move public state and ballot reducers into Rust so Rust becomes the reducer source of truth rather than TypeScript.

### Intended scope

- public event types in Rust
- ballot event types in Rust
- public round reducer in Rust
- ballot acceptance reducer in Rust
- mixed replay for public + ballot + coordinator streams
- UI consumption of Rust-derived state

### Implemented

Rust modules added/expanded:

- `auditable-voting-core/src/event.rs`
- `auditable-voting-core/src/public_state.rs`
- `auditable-voting-core/src/ballot_state.rs`
- `auditable-voting-core/src/reducer.rs`
- `auditable-voting-core/src/validation.rs`
- `auditable-voting-core/src/wasm.rs`

TS adapter/bridge modules added:

- `web/src/core/publicEventBridge.ts`
- `web/src/core/ballotEventBridge.ts`
- `web/src/core/derivedStateAdapter.ts`

Shared protocol-state service added:

- `web/src/services/ProtocolStateService.ts`

Tests added:

- `web/src/core/derivedStateAdapter.test.ts`
- `web/src/services/ProtocolStateService.test.ts`

### Rust-derived behaviour now present

- deterministic mixed replay
- public round lifecycle derivation
- ballot acceptance with a fixed `first valid wins` rule
- accepted/rejected ballot derivation
- round summaries
- snapshot export/import for the protocol replay engine

### UI migration status

Now on the Rust-derived public-state path:

- auditor public-state view
- coordinator submitted-votes public-state view
- voter public round selection / known-round public-state view

Still not fully migrated:

- some private issuance/ticket state in voter and coordinator flows remains TypeScript-owned by design
- some legacy TS helper modules still exist in the tree, even when no longer authoritative for the migrated slice

### Status

`Substantially completed for the public-state migration slice.`

### Remaining gap inside Phase 2

- remove or archive obsolete TS reducer helpers once their remaining tests/references are resolved cleanly
- expand parity/integration coverage beyond the current focused tests

